Gaucher's disease in children: Case report from Afghanistan with literature review

## A R T I C L E I N F O

Keywords:

Gaucher's disease

Genetic disorder

Hepatosoplegianemaly

Thrombocytopenia

Enzyme replacement therapy

Splenectomy

Splenectomy

Introduction and importance: Gaucher's disease (GD) or lysosomal storage disease, is one of the rare genetic disorders resulting from glucocerebroside deficiency. Clinical manifestations include a swollen belly (heptosoplegianemaly), bruising due to thrombocytopenia, anemia, fatigue, bone pain, and neurological involvement. Diagnosis is made by measuring the level of glucocerebrosease enzyme in the blood, using dual energy X-ray absorptiometry (DXA), and performing genetic tests. For some types of GD, enzyme therapy is now available. Case presentation: A 5-year-old child with a high-grade fever and splenomegaly was admitted to our teaching hospital's pediatric surgery department. The patient had genetic screening in early childhood outside the country, confirming the diagnosis of GD. Following the appropriate anti-bacterial therapy, the patient underwent splenectomy for conditions such as splenomegaly, lack of enzyme replacement therapy, and the patient's susceptibility to trauma.

Clinical discussion: GD is a rare disease that is frequently coupled with thalassemia. If there are no visible signs and symptoms, the disease is overlooked and left untreated. Our clinical justifications for surgical operation (splenectomy) were splenomegaly, lack of enzyme replacement therapy (an integral part of gaucher's disease treatment), and prevention of spleniceptic rupture (as a result of falling down due to child neglect, which is common in Afghanistan). During the 1-year post-operative follow-up, our patient experienced two episodes of high-grade fever, which were treated appropriately.

Conclusion: Due to the rarity of GD, the disease is left untreated and undiagnosed for a long time, mainly in developing countries where definite diagnostic modalities are not readily available. Diseases with similar symptoms should always be considered in the differential diagnosis. Early enzyme replacement therapy is the key to improve the quality of life, but it is not available in developing nations.

## Case presentation

A 5-year-old boy was brought to our teaching hospital's pediatric surgery department by his parents with a high-grade fever and visce -omegally (hepatosplenomegaly). The patient was born to a couple with a second-degree consanguinity and a negative family history for the mentioned and other medical conditions. According to the parents' explanation, the patient's abdomen began to expand at the 8th month of age with mild anemia. The condition gradually progressed until they had to see a physician.

The primary treatment was ineffective, so they took their child out of the country for a better remedy. There, the patient was diagnosed with glycogen storage disease and advised to be fed with lactose-free milk. Meanwhile, he was diagnosed genetically with GD. The parents returned to Afghanistan and followed the mentioned regimen with appropriate medication for their child. Since then, the patient required blood transfusions (BT) on a regular basis in every six-month interval, but the frequency gradually decreased to once a month and, on referral to our department, twice a month. On admission to our pediatric service, due to having a high-grade fever as a result of a chest infection, the relevant medical therapy was initiated and followed until the patient became fever-free. Now the patient was checked clinically, and all the necessary routine and biochemical laboratory tests were performed, along with whole abdomen ultrasonography (USGC) and computerized tomography (CT-scan) confirming visceromegaly (a huge spleen with the tip extending to the pelvic cavity) (Fig. 1).

Based on the clinical condition, we decided to proceed with the splenectomy (Fig. 2). The whole resected spleen was sent by the mean of specimen for histopathology analysis, which confirmed GD (Figs. 3 and 4). Our team followed the patient for twelve post-operative months without any clinical concern.

## Discussion and conclusion

Gaucher's disease (GD), described in 1882 by Philippe Charles Ernest Gaucher, is considered a pan-ethnic disease. It has a global prevalence of 1 in 50,000-100,000, but it could be as high as 1 in 850 in the Ashkenazi

Jewish population. 7 In medical literature, the disease is classified into three categories: Type I, also known as adult or non-neuropathic GD, is distinguished by the absence of significant neurological impairment; Type II, or acute neuropathic form, is distinguished by the presence of a very early clinical scenario and significant neurological impairment; and Type III, or sub-acute neuropathic form, is less severe and similar

to type II 8. The disease has an equal sex distribution. The onset age ranges from one month 9 to 80 years. 10 Some of the type 1 GD samples may present in early childhood with all of the GD complications, whereas the others will remain asymptomatic until the eighth decade of life with the incidental presentation of thrombocytopenia or splenemegaly. Many patients remain asymptomatic and don't seek medical attention. However, 66% of type 1 GD sufferers are from 1 month to 7 age of 20. 1 Typically, types 2 and 3 manifest in early childhood. The lag time between disease onset and diagnosis ranges from 1 month to 7 years, with an average of 2.3 years. Delayed diagnosis is caused by a lack of suspicion for GD and its rarity. Type 1 G has a rapid onset and manifests with splenemegaly, in which the spleen tip extends to the pelvis. 12,13 Skeletal manifestations of the GD range from the Erlenmeyer flask deformity (reduced femoral constriction of the diaphragm and flaring of its metaphysis of the distal femur to pathologic fractures, vertebral collapse, and acute bone crisis, which is mostly confused with acute osteomyelitis. Leg-Cave-Perthes diseases (childhood hip disorder) initiated by a disruption of blood flow to the head of the femur) can be misinterpreted as an acute hip lesion in children. Hap vascular necrosis is a common complication in individuals of all ages. Hematologic manifestations of GD include pancytopenia with anemia, thrombocytopenia, and less commonly, leucopenia. 14 Chronic fatigue with short stature, which is the result of energy expenditure needed by the enlarged organs, could also be noted. 7

Type 2 GD is rare and has a rapid neurodegenerative course with substantial visceral involvement and death within 2 years of age. This type of disease may present at birth or infancy with increased tone, seizures, stabilismus, swallowing abnormalities, failure to thrive, and oculomotor apraxia. Stridor due to laryngospasm is typical in infants with type 2 disease. 15-18 Aspiration and respiratory compromise due to progressive psychomotor degeneration and brain stem involvement may lead to death.

Type 3 GD may also be present in infancy and childhood. In this type of disease, besides organeglyory and bony involvement, neurologic involvement is common, and the patient may experience myoclonic epilepsy. Laboratory tests include enzyme activity tests, which is confirmed through the measurement of glucocebrosidase activity in peripheral blood leukocytes. The histopathologic finding of the disease is the presence of the gaucher cell in the macrophage-monocyte system, particularly in the bone marrow or in liver biopsy samples. 19 Genotype testing and phenotype-genotype correlation and complexity are other diagnostic tools, more than 200 different mutant GABA alleles have been identified in patients with GD. 20-22

Treatment of GD includes enzyme replacement therapy (ERT), substrate reduction therapy (SRT), and supportive therapy. Therapeutic goals for children with GD are related to the common manifestations such as anemia, thrombocytopenia, hepatosophytelenome, bone disease, and growth retardation. Nowadays, The ERT is only the treatment option for pediatrics with symptomatic GD, with varying tissue uptake. ERT (recommended starting dose for children 30-60 U/kg every other week with later adjustments based on clinical response and the achievement of therapeutic goals) provides the breakdown of substrate(s), visceral improvement, normalization of growth, and bone manifestations. 24 Three approved ERTs (Imiglucerase, Velaglucerase and Alfa, and Taliuglucerase alfa) are available in the USA. Oral SRTs (glucosylceramide synthase inhibitor) miglustat and eligustal are approved for the GD treatment in adults. SRTs reduce the amount of substrate precursor synthesized and restore metabolic homeostasis, thereby reducing required catabolism, to a level that can be cleared by residual mutant Gcase activity. 25 Next-generation SRT, gene therapy, and pharmacological chaperones are the investigative treatments for GD. Venglustat is a small molecule, glucosylceramide synthase inhibitor (SRT), penetrating the CNS and is an investigative treatment for type 3 GD. 20 Gene therapy causes the introduction of GBA into hematopoietic stem cells, liver cells, and, conceivably, brain cells through a vector-mediated process. 25

In type 1 GD, ERT decreases hepatosplenomegaly, increases hemoglobin level, platelet count, and improves child growth and bone mineral density (BMD). Additionally, ERT improves health-related quality of life (HRQoI) in children; clinical benefits have been proven in clinical trials and real-world registry studies. The literature focuses on the first ERT for the GD, aluglucase, and its replacement, imiglucerase. 24,27 ERT significantly improves somatic manifestations in type 1 and 3 GD. Since ERT isn't able to cross the blood-brain barrier, its use is not recommended in type 2 GD.

GD management must be evaluated at regular intervals using MRI, DXA imaging, laboratory biochemical tests, and measurement of the biomarker level in children receiving ERT. Sensitive indicators of the ERT response are the normalization of the cytopenias and the volume of the liver and spleen. 24,29

Optimal management of the GD requires a multidisciplinary approach. 22 Blood transfusion, orthopedic surgery, the use of predilones, non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs (NSAIDs), and supplemental, calcium such as calcium and vitamin D (24, 25). Pathologic fractures and other bone complications, such as avascular necrosis, may require orthopedic surgery. For the treatment of GD-related osteopenia and osteoporosis, anti-bone-responsive treatments such as bisphosphonates and calcium with vitamin D supplements may be needed. However, the use of bisphosphonates is rarely indicated in children since they may cause an acute-phase reaction (flu-like symptoms), gastrointestinal irritation, chemical esophagitis, and muscles or bone pain. 30 Predisnolise is effective for relieving pain during acute bone crises in children. During an acute bone crisis, temporary immobilization and good hydration are important. Non-specific pain could be treated with acetaminophen and NSAIDs. In patients with moderate to severe thrombocytopenia and other hemolytic disorders, NSAIDs should be avoided. In severe pain, opioids could also be used. Physiotherapy, occupational therapy, massage therapy, and electrical nerve stimulation are other modalities to reduce pain. 25,31,32

Total or partial splenectomy is rarely indicated, but in exceptional circumstances, such as those not receiving ERT, life-threatening bleeding, non-response to ERT with sever thrombocytopenia, patients with splenurept, and painful splenomegaly with marked areas of infarction, microfenismy may be necessary. 23,25

The index case was diagnosed outside the country after undergoing genetic screening, which revealed GD. The patient's initial admission was due to a high-grade fever and splenomegaly. Following appropriate treatment, we planned a splenectomy for the following reasons: lack of ERT (an integral part of gaucher disease treatment), his parents' insistence, and our justification to improve anemia and prevent splenic rupture due to the patient's accidental fall (as a result of child neglect, which is common in Afghanistan). For boosting the immune system, three weeks prior to splenectomy, the patient received pneumococci, meningocci, and H. influnenza vaccinations (our standard protocol for splenectomy). We performed a splenectomy, so the patient's condition improved (anoxia and early satiety), and the anemia was relieved. Contrary to the literature, our patient exhibited no evident bone involvement, but based on the literature, our patient suffered from chronic fatigue and short stature. Neurological involvement was not present in our patient. Based on the clinical picture mentioned, our patient was categorized as having type 1 GD. In Afghanistan, ERT is not readily available (it may be available in some regions outside the country, but at a high cost), and the treatment is almost symptomatic and palliative. To date, during the 1-year post-operative follow-up, the patient was admitted twice to our pediatric service complaining of a high-grade fever and treated appropriately. The reason could be due to a post-splenectomy infection.
